10.body: By the end of this lab, students will be able to: Successfully install the R programming language. Install the RStudio Desktop Integrated Development Environment (IDE). Verify the installation by running a simple command.
10.breadcrumbs: Lab 1: R and RStudio Installation » Learning Objectives
10.title: Learning Objectives

11.body: To perform data science at DCC, we use two primary tools. Think of R as the "engine" of a car and RStudio as the "dashboard." You need the engine to go, but you need the dashboard to steer and see where you are going. If you are using a DCC Chromebook or a computer where you cannot install software, please contact the instructor about using **Posit Cloud** (the web-based version of RStudio).
11.breadcrumbs: Lab 1: R and RStudio Installation » Introduction
11.title: Introduction

12.body: You must install R before you install RStudio. Go to the CRAN (Comprehensive R Archive Network) website. Select the download link for your operating system: Download R for Windows -> Click "base" -> Click "Download R 4.x.x for Windows." Download R for (macOS) -> Download the .pkg file that matches your chip (Apple silicon M1/M2 or Intel). Run the downloaded installer and keep all default settings by clicking "Next" or "Continue."
12.breadcrumbs: Lab 1: R and RStudio Installation » Step 1: Install R (The Engine)
12.title: Step 1: Install R (The Engine)

13.body: RStudio is the interface where you will write your code and view your data visualizations. Visit the Posit Download Page . Scroll down to "2: Install RStudio" and click the button for your operating system. Run the installer. Like R, it is best to keep all default settings.
13.breadcrumbs: Lab 1: R and RStudio Installation » Step 2: Install RStudio (The Dashboard)
13.title: Step 2: Install RStudio (The Dashboard)

14.body: Let's make sure the "engine" and "dashboard" are talking to each other. Open RStudio from your applications folder or start menu. Find the Console pane (usually on the bottom left). Type the following code and press Enter : print("Hello, MAT 186!")

14.title: Step 3: Verify Your Setup

15.title: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto Documents

16.body: Create an RStudio Project to organize your work. Understand the structure of a Quarto (.qmd) document. "Render" a document into a professional HTML report.
16.breadcrumbs: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto » Learning Objectives
16.title: Learning Objectives

17.body: In Data Science, organization is everything. An RStudio Project keeps your code, data, and images in one "folder" so R always knows where to look. Open RStudio. Click File > New Project... Select New Directory > New Project . Name your directory MAT186_Labs and save it to your Desktop or Documents. **Why use Projects?** It sets the "Working Directory" automatically. You'll never have to type long file paths like `C:/Users/Documents/Data...` again!
17.breadcrumbs: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto » Part 1: RStudio Projects
17.title: Part 1: RStudio Projects

18.body: Quarto allows you to combine text, code, and results in one file. Click File > New File > Quarto Document... Title it "Lab 2" and put your name as the Author. Click Create . Look at the file. You will see: YAML Header: The stuff between the --- lines (Title, Author, Format). Code Chunks: The gray boxes starting with ```{r}. Markdown: The plain white areas for your written analysis.
18.breadcrumbs: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto » Part 2: Creating a Quarto Document
18.title: Part 2: Creating a Quarto Document

19.body: To turn your code into a report: Click the Render button (blue arrow icon) at the top of the editor. RStudio will save the file and pop up a beautiful HTML window. **Lab Task 2:** Inside your Quarto document, create a new code chunk and type `2 + 2`. Render the document and verify that the number `4` appears in the final report. Screenshot your rendered HTML for submission.
19.breadcrumbs: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto » Part 3: Rendering (The "Magic" Button)
19.title: Part 3: Rendering (The "Magic" Button)

3.body: CRAN (Comprehensive R Archive Network): The global network of servers that stores and distributes R and its packages. Think of it as the "App Store" for R.
3.title: C

4.body: Data Frame: A table-like structure in R where each column represents a variable and each row represents an observation.
4.title: D

5.body: IDE (Integrated Development Environment): A software application (like RStudio) that provides comprehensive facilities to computer programmers for software development.
5.title: I

6.body: Markdown: A lightweight markup language with plain-text-formatting syntax. It allows you to write formatted text that can be easily converted to HTML.
6.title: M

7.body: Quarto: The next-generation version of RMarkdown. It is an open-source scientific and technical publishing system used to create documents, books, and websites.
7.title: Q

8.body: YAML: Stands for "Yet Another Markup Language." In Quarto, the YAML header (at the top of the file) is where you define settings like the title, author, and output format.
8.title: Y
